// ERROR: nullable struct return
// WO-2 Lát A T5' (ADR-0065 §14.6, 2026-07-20 — NARROWED, revised from the
// original WO-StructReturnRefuse T4, 2026-07-19): `Struct?` in RETURN
// position where the struct has a HEAP-bearing field (`String`) STAYS
// REFUSED after Lát A. Unlike 437-439 (all-scalar Copy `P`/`Outer`, which
// now run via full-SRET), this shape is a permanent DESIGN FENCE, not a
// temporary policy gate: ADR-0065 §4 (B8, locked) restricts `Struct?`/
// `Enum?` to Copy-only fields/payload ("KHÔNG DROP GLUE. KHÔNG ALLOC.
// KHÔNG FREE.") — the tag-prepend sret buffer carries no drop-glue, so a
// heap leaf in it would leak or double-free. The refuse fires via a NEW,
// NARROWER gate (`nullable_struct_return_heap_field_unsupported`,
// `ctx_is_copy`-gated) that replaces the old unconditional
// `nullable_struct_return_unsupported` — it fires ONLY for a non-Copy
// (heap-bearing) struct now, not for every `Nullable(Struct)` return.
// Pre-any-guard measured on 768fc8e: `check` phase passed (exit 0, no
// refuse anywhere), then `run` ABORTED — SIGABRT 134, "free(): invalid
// pointer" (drop-glue running on an uninitialized pointer from the garbage
// Scalar-shaped return slot). This fixture is the teeth pinning that this
// abort path stays closed under the narrowed, Copy-aware gate.
struct H { name: String }

function make() -> H? {
    return ~0;
}

function main() -> Integer {
    return match make() {
        ~+ v => 1,
        ~0 => 0,
    };
}
